Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and who are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a spine of dinosaur and the balconies to the mouths of open fish.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house received the nickname House in bones from the premises.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present of curves, here's all that's ypic for Art New of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house runs its dream lines, its colours and pleasant textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit so that the impression of brightness of the colors is strengthened.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyepiece and the blades.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in Passeig de Gracia market street at the number. 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house ended in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first stressed the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of unusual and better-selling reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a house with multiple dwellings was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for an apartment for the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
Other artists and creators also worked for the facade.
The joint work on the plans of the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park where there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises nicknamed the house hot just after its completion due to its organic forms "the House in Bones".
Others, in view of the specific window opening mechanism, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with aeration events and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely failed to comply with the then construction directives and was not hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permit to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and requested modifications.
He did not, for example, like the members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction stumble on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) for permission to rent the two top floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third room there was a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is divided by a staircase through which you can reach up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space linkage.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi also received new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the wells of light.
The two-coloured game gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark which instead absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued their visits because they found it to be a profitable business and expanded the scope of visits to common spaces and to the barn, including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket in the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other constructions of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a friend among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
