Devices to track people are increasingly being requested by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up in the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as for example that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a light box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," said Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracing devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of someone who is not aware of it, but I have not yet met such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," Pilin adds.
He said children should always know what "box" is used for and how to use it in the event of an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
'Even smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something deliberately when they don't want to be under control.'
"The mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already led the parents to long expectations," Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"If this is a prepared rapture, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"Now it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
It also admits that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to RC Monitoring company Robert Cech, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular emission after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains nevertheless."
'The most expensive devices also have a tiltometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in a lying position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after having formed it with a special prological.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to those used in pendants of the size of a light box or to smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are being carried out to make devices similar to common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the possible attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll figure it out after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to plot cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
