A longer index than the annullary is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the longest index than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by British Cancer magazine.
This may depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years of age," said the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
This could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health records, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular.
For them as well as for 19 percent of those whose fingers were of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the longest index than the annual risk, however, fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years of age the risk decrease reached 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, inter alia, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less than testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is precisely what helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former President of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
