Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign with charges.
The prosecutors of the Department of Justice lifted the criminal charges brought on Senator John Ensign, arising from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the husband of the woman, announced Wednesday the Senator's lawyers.
The decision put an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate to the 2012 presidential election until the scandal around his case did not make the big national titles last year and damage his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" with the decision, resulting from a one-year investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "reported that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charge against him in this case."
The Ministry of Justice abstained on this matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many lawyers of ethics outside the Ministry of Justice, who said there would be significant evidence that Mr. Ensign would have intended to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, obtain a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's case with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for a year by the law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called prohibition of the rotating lobbying door.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a plot to violate and substantially violate the law of the rotating door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of an investigation by the government.
Although the Department's judge refused to explain the reasoning leading to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be suspicious of political prosecutions after a number of high-level cashbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government official can now assumes the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Chief Counsel of Mr. Ensign, stated in an interview that he had received a phone call from a prosecutor of the Department of Justice on Monday and followed up the following day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with the prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed in a press release Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made at the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable getting into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, claiming that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to Hampton violated the federal electoral law.
The Electoral Commission stated that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was all except a gift.
NV Energy, an important Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company hosted Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, the Chief of Staff of Mr. Ensign, John Lopez, communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he "martled" the Ministry of the Interior on a dispute issue.
Mr. Ensign also participated in a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another client from Nevada, Allegian Air, and asked the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after having engaged Mr. Hampton in lobbying.
When the news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as leader at the fourth Republican position in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to hold a third term in the Senate.
By announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said that the senator hoped that the Ethics Committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and put an end to his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
