Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge visited the government, long-standing loyalty was finally called into question at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum of truth and reconciliation enabled victims to face publicly the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, taught the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led with the United Nations, issued its first sentence concerning a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious torture centre of Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Yev, better known as "Duch".
Faced with this changing situation, anxiety has increased among the veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng; making reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There are resentments and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Centre, an independent agency that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the red Khmer was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
Under the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overcrowding.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrowed the government of Pol Pot-Uni in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the border of Cambodia with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements took place in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrillas of their base located in the western mountains of Cambodia and the jungle, Ta Mok prepared a follow-up in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a United Nations-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Red fighters began to defeat the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had taken the lead, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending his trial.
Without their beneficiaries, most of the former Khmer Red fighters have obscured the black poverty common in rural areas of Cambodia, and many remain nostalgic in the movement.
Although some Khmer Red elite officers have retained their positions as local leader in exchange for having laid down their weapons, these are low-grade and record-qualified farmers.
"These people received very little follow-up after capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are embroiled in the utopian ideology of the regime."
"They were raised in a context where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice grower.
"Life under the red Khmer was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to support our own needs."
