The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People must go to Visa Applicant Service centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cut of waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the visa treatment procedure at the Embassy and consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview with the Consular Section.
The CSA staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will present certain benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a need to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas on request (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for trade and investor visas.
Those wishing to renew their visas will not have to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves at the nearest SAC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be collected in the CSA, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boltines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
