A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
In Cancún yesterday, the United Nations proposed a renewal plan for domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction, which corresponds almost to a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan lies in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the absence of binding commitments for reductions by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED", in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to enlighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, the major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should move global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract 5 Gt from this balance to stabilise the 2 degree centigrade climate by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates as heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced by two more times.
Fluocompact bulbs last from 6000 to 10 000 hours on average.
New LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the United Nations study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consumes 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with an alternative plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats as well as emit very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have posted reserves for fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place seals.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost it 2.5 billion.
