Revenge hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of hypocrisy which governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by the regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is exclusively made up of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations on the sexual habits of Berlusconi only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and the caricature sinister profile of Khadafi has long been for artists of cabaret material to sketch.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, not just in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous works.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (he doesn't know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism only believe what they already know, and who reaffirms what they have already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) the head of secret services (unless he could be, I know, editor of Liberation), who only retain what he recognizes as true.
The top secret information on Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every person cultivated already knows, that the embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since the Heads of State can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world brings a significant blow to the prestige of the state department.
So the scandal doesn't put both the victims and the "bourreaux" in so much crisis.
But let's come to the deep nature of what happened.
So in Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, having been able to control each movement through the telephone, each transaction carried out, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the power eye.
But when it is shown, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected revenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of the power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret of secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put online any reserved information - it would be possible to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is as obvious as with current technologies, it is futile to hope to maintain confidential telephone relations.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction falls within the scope of science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials moving discreetly in due diligence to uncontrollable itineraries, being only bearers of messages learned by heart or, at the most, concealing the few information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in key-closed drawers: at the bottom, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I've had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving in crabs, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegrapher revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a telegraph on wire (telephones).
Videocassettes (analogiques) had allowed film researchers to explore a step-by-step film, going forward and back, and discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digitals) allow them to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while flying, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the communication policy and techniques return to the horse cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
It is now the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France bidouilles its promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine compliance with the promises of quick and early fast-start and early-earned funding made by developed countries.
And the big French biduillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU came out the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and valued at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with equal precision.
The EU announces that it has made €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the best reference.
For example, the European Commission considered the year 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years to fast start financing.
Other countries have selected similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or at the overall level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France's support for developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ borrowed equals 1€ given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has only such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice walk-by tour!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand, on the evolution of action over time and on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it is believed that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has done the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in negotiations since developing countries are not completely dupe...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are recorded will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of a kind to increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
